data.content:
Three breaking changes hit your code. Here's each one and the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now takes `Func`, not `Expression<Func>`

Your manual expression-tree building **won't compile** because the overload now accepts a plain lambda. Replace the entire block:

```csharp
// EF Core 10 — no expression trees needed
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

---

### 2. Complex type columns — two changes

**a) Shared column names are now uniquified.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously silently shared one `Street` column; now EF appends a number (e.g. `Street`, `Street1`). To keep the old schema, pin names explicitly:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was mapped to `BillingAddress_City`; now it becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method (`CommandReaderExecuting`, `CommandReaderExecuted`, etc.) gained a `string logCommandText` parameter for redacted SQL logging. Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)        // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText (sensitive data redacted) for logging
        // Use command.CommandText for actual execution logic
    }
}
```

---

**TL;DR:** Delete your expression-tree plumbing (it's just `if` statements now), add `.HasColumnName()` to complex properties if you need to preserve existing column names, and add `string logCommandText` to every diagnostics logger method.
